Definition 4.8. Let $\partial:\Gamma\to G_{0}$ denote the restriction of the source map $\mathbf{s}:G_{1}\to G_{0}$ to $\Gamma$. Define, for all $\gamma\in\Gamma$ and all $x\in G_{0}$, $\displaystyle\gamma\cdot x$ $\displaystyle:=\partial(\gamma)\otimes x$ $\displaystyle x*\gamma$ $\displaystyle:=x\otimes\gamma\otimes\overline{x}.$
Definition 2.15. We say that a coherent Lie 2-group is base connected, when the base manifold of its underlying Lie groupoid is connected.
Definition 3.1. A flow in ${\mathfrak{X}}$ is a pair $(X,\phi)$, where $X$ is an object in $\mathfrak{X}$ and $\phi:X\to X$ an endomorphism in ${\mathfrak{X}}$.
Definition 2.12. A pair $(\mathcal{T},\mathcal{F})$ of non-empty subclasses of an abelian category $\mathfrak{M}$ is a torsion theory in $\mathfrak{M}$ if: (i) $\mathcal{T}\cap\mathcal{F}=\{0\}$; (ii) if $T\to A\to 0$ is exact with $T\in\mathcal{T}$, then $A\in\mathcal{T}$; (iii) if $0\to A\to F$ is exact with $F\in\mathcal{F}$, then $A\in\mathcal{F}$; (iv) for every $M\in\mathfrak{M}$ there exists an exact sequence $0\to T\to M\to F\to 0$ with $T\in\mathcal{T}$ and $F\in\mathcal{F}$.
Definition 4.1. Let $(M,\phi)\in\mathbf{Flow}_{R}$. An element $x\in M$ is a quasi-periodic point of $\phi$ if there exist $n>m$ in $\mathbb{N}$ such that $\phi^{n}(x)=\phi^{m}(x)$. Moreover, $\phi$ is pointwise quasi-periodic if every $x\in M$ is a quasi-periodic point of $\phi$; and $\phi$ is quasi-periodic if there exist $n>m$ in $\mathbb{N}$ such that $\phi^{n}=\phi^{m}$.
Definition 2.15. For a torsion theory $\mathfrak{t}_{\mathbf{r}}$ in $\mathfrak{M}$, a subobject $N$ of $M\in\mathfrak{M}$ is $\mathfrak{t}_{\mathbf{r}}$-closed if $\mathbf{r}(M/N)=0$. More generally, the $\mathfrak{t}_{\mathbf{r}}$-closure $\mathrm{cl}_{\mathfrak{t}_{\mathbf{r}}}(N)$ of a subobject $N$ of $M$ is the pullback of $\mathbf{r}(M/N)$ along the projection $M\to M/N$.
Definition 1.1. An entropy function $h$ of $\mathfrak{M}$ is a function $h:\mathfrak{M}\to\mathbb{R}_{+}\cup\{\infty\}$ such that: (A1) $h(0)=0$ and $h(M)=h(N)$ if $M$ and $N$ are isomorphic objects in $\mathfrak{M}$; (A2) $h(M)=0$ if and only if $h(N)=0=h(Q)$ for every exact sequence $0\longrightarrow N\longrightarrow M\longrightarrow Q\longrightarrow 0$ in $\mathfrak{M}$; (A3) for a set $\{M_{j}:j\in I\}$ of objects of $\mathfrak{M}$, $h(\bigoplus_{j\in J}M_{j})=0$ if and only if $h(M_{j})=0$ for all $j\in J$. An entropy function $h$ of $\mathfrak{M}$ is binary if it takes only the values $0$ and $\infty$.
Definition 2.16. For $h\in\mathfrak{H}(\mathfrak{M})$ we call $\mathfrak{t}_{h}$ the Pinsker torsion theory of $h$ in $\mathfrak{M}$.
Definition 2.8. Let $h\in\mathfrak{H}(\mathfrak{M})$. The Pinsker radical $\mathbf{P}_{h}:\mathfrak{M}\to\mathfrak{M}$ with respect to $h$ is defined for every object $M$ of $\mathfrak{M}$ as the join $\mathbf{P}_{h}(M)=\sum\{N_{j}\subseteq M:h(N_{j})=0\}.$
Definition 2.5. The binary hull of $h\in\mathfrak{H}(\mathfrak{M})$ is the smallest $h^{b}\in\mathfrak{H}_{b}(\mathfrak{M})$ above $h$, i.e., $h^{b}=\inf\{h^{\prime}\in\mathfrak{H}_{b}(\mathfrak{M}):h^{\prime}\succ h\}.$
Definition 3.12. [NR] An additive upper continuous invariant is called length function.
Definition 2.14. A torsion theory $(\mathcal{T},\mathcal{F})$ in $\mathfrak{M}$ is hereditary if $\mathcal{T}$ is closed under subobjects.
Definition 5.12. If $B$ and $B^{\prime}$ are nontrivial $\stackrel{{\scriptstyle d}}{{\sim}}$-equivalence classes with minimal diagrams $\lambda$ and $\lambda^{\prime}$ respectively, we write $B\prec B^{\prime}$ if $\lambda(d)\prec\lambda^{\prime}(d)$ (see section 1.1).
Definition 3.18. $\mathcal{F}:\underline{\operatorname{Re}}\!\operatorname{p}(S_{d};F)\to% \operatorname{Rep}(S_{d};F)$ is the functor defined on indecomposable objects by $\mathcal{F}([n],e)=f(e)(V_{d}^{\otimes n})$, and on morphisms $\alpha:([n],e)\to([n^{\prime}],e^{\prime})$ by $\mathcal{F}(\alpha)=f(\alpha)$. Here $f$ and $V_{d}$ are as in section 2.1.
Definition 2.7. Given partition diagrams $\pi\in P_{n,m}$ and $\mu\in P_{m,l}$, construct a new diagram $\mu\star\pi$ by identifying the vertices $1^{\prime},\ldots,m^{\prime}$ of $\pi$ with the vertices $1,\ldots,m$ of $\mu$ and renaming them $1^{\prime\prime},\ldots,m^{\prime\prime}$ as illustrated below. Now let $\ell(\mu,\pi)$ denote the number of connected components of $\mu\star\pi$ whose vertices are not among $1,\ldots,n,1^{\prime},\ldots,l^{\prime}$. Finally, let $\mu\cdot\pi\in P_{n,l}$ be the partition obtained by restricting $\mu\star\pi$ to $\{1,\ldots,n,1^{\prime},\ldots,l^{\prime}\}$ (i.e. $r$ and $s$ are in the same part of $\mu\cdot\pi$ if and only if $r$ and $s$ are in the same part of $\mu\star\pi$).
Definition 2.15. For objects $[n],[m]$ in $\underline{\operatorname{Re}}\!\operatorname{p}_{0}(S_{t};F)$ set $[n]\otimes[m]:=[n+m]$. For morphisms we let $\otimes:FP_{n_{1},m_{1}}\times FP_{n_{2},m_{2}}\to FP_{n_{1}+n_{2},m_{1}+m_{2}}$ be the bilinear map such that for all $\pi\in P_{n_{1},m_{1}}$, $\mu\in P_{n_{2},m_{2}}$.
Definition 4.2. For nonnegative integers $r,n,$ and $d$ with $r\leq d$ and $2n\leq d$, let $C_{n}^{r}(d)$ denote the unique element of $FP_{n}(d)$ with $f(C_{n}^{r}(d))\in\text{End}_{S_{d}}(V_{d}^{\otimes n})$ given by the action of $\Omega_{r,d}$.
